UMUAHIA – Chief Judge of Abia State, Justice Onuoha Arisa Kalu, has finally inaugurated the State Ad­ministration of Criminal Justice Monitoring Com­mittee Secretariat, five years after cueing into the Federal Administration of Criminal Justice Act Law which came into effect in the state on December 22, 2017 as law of the state. Section 456 of the State Administration of Crimi­nal Justice Law provides for the establishment of a functional secretariat which would see to the efficient running of the committee. Justice Kalu was repre­sented by Justice Chijioke Okereke, who also present­ed his address. -Advertisement- He disclosed that the Chief Judge was absent from the inauguration and training workshop spon­sored in partnership with the Federal ACJMC due to an official engagement out­side the state. Justice Onuoha de­scribed the inauguration of the monitoring com­mittee as a turning point in the life of the commit­tee in the state as well as the training workshop sponsored by Mac Arthur Foundation, which he said, would be fun and full of learning. “It is surely the begin­ning of great things to hap­pen in the administration of Criminal Justice Sector of the state and to the bet­terment of all good and law abiding citizens and resi­dents of this state” The Chief Judge ex­pressed his appreciation to the Federal Adminis­tration of Criminal Jus­tice Monitoring Commit­tee for its support and partnership with the State Administration of Crimi­nal Justice Committee and for office equipment they have provided and pre­sented to the secretariat of the monitoring committee. According to the State Chief Judge, the train­ing would help the par­ticipants to hone in on the State Administration of Criminal Justice Law, 2017, “But more impor­tantly, we will spend valu­able one-on-one time with beach and every one of you so that you will know that your is not only being heard, but valued.” POLL Earlier in his address, the Executive Secretary of Criminal Justice Admin­istration, Federal Secre­tariat, Abuja, Sulyman Dawodu, commended the state for cuing fully into the Administration of Criminal Justice Law by inaugurating a Monitor­ing Committee and estab­lishing a secretariat.